                    "text_V3dHLP": {
                      "type": "text",
                      "settings": {
                        "text": "<p>Echeverias are among the most popular succulents, admired for their perfect rosettes, vibrant colours, and wide variety of forms. Native to Mexico and Central America, they thrive in sunny, arid conditions – but with the right care, they adapt beautifully to life in the UK. Here’s everything you need to know to keep your plants healthy, colourful, and thriving.</p><h4><strong>Light</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Echeverias love <strong>bright, direct light</strong>. Outdoors in the UK, they do best in full sun during spring and summer.<br/></li><li>Indoors, place them on the <strong>brightest south-facing windowsill</strong> or under grow lights to maintain compact rosettes and strong colour.<br/></li><li>Without enough light, they may stretch (etiolate), losing their neat shape.</li></ul><h4><strong>Watering (3Ds Method: Drench, Drain, Dry)</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Water thoroughly, allowing the soil to <strong>drench</strong> and excess to <strong>drain</strong>.<br/></li><li>Always let the soil <strong>dry completely</strong> before watering again.<br/></li><li>In summer, this may be once every 1–2 weeks; in winter, much less.<br/></li><li>Avoid watering into the rosette as it can cause rot.</li></ul><h4><strong>Soil & Repotting</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Use a <strong>free-draining mix</strong>: 1/3 John Innes no2 compost, 1/3 grit/perlite and 1/3 coconut coir.<br/></li><li>Repot every 1–2 years in spring to refresh nutrients and encourage growth.<br/></li><li>Plant slightly above the soil line and use a <strong>grit/ gravel top dressing</strong> to protect leaves from damp soil.</li><li>Use a pot that is <strong>around the same diameter of the plant</strong>. Too big of a pot and the plant can become <strong>waterlogged</strong>. They like to have cramped roots as this stresses them, bringing out <strong>hardiness and colour</strong>. Shallow pots are <strong>perfect</strong>.</li></ul><h4><strong>Winter Care (UK Specific)</strong></h4><h2></h2><ul><li>Most Echeverias are <strong>not entirely frost hardy</strong> (generally below 0°C will damage them).<br/></li><li>Overwinter under cover: a <strong>cool, airy greenhouse, porch, or bright windowsill</strong>.<br/></li><li>Protect with <a href=\"/products/horticultural-fleece\" title=\"Horticultural Fleece\"><strong>horticultural fleece</strong></a> if temperatures dip suddenly.<br/></li><li>Don't water in winter – Echeveria are dormant in winter and prefer to stay on the dry side. Give them a tiny drink if desperate.</li></ul><h4><strong>Growth & Flowering</strong></h4><h2></h2><ul><li>Echeverias usually grow actively in spring and summer.<br/></li><li>Many produce <strong>colourful, arching flower spikes</strong> in late spring/summer that attract pollinators.<br/></li><li>After flowering, remove the stem to keep rosettes tidy.</li></ul><h4><strong>Propagation</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li>Easily propagated by <strong>leaf cuttings, offsets, or seed</strong>.<br/></li><li>Gently twist a full, healthy leaf from the base, allow to callous, then place on dry gritty soil.<br/></li><li>Offsets (‘pups’) can be separated and replanted in their own pot.</li></ul><h4><strong>Common Issues</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li><strong>Rot</strong>: caused by excess water, poor drainage or lack of fresh air flow.<br/></li><li><strong>Stretching</strong>: not enough light – move to a sunnier spot.<br/></li><li><strong>Vine weevils</strong>: give them a wobbke test. If wobbly, inspect roots and if maggots present, refresh soil.</li></ul><h4><strong>Key Tips for UK Growers</strong></h4><h4></h4><ul><li><strong>Summer</strong>: Grow outside in full sun for the best colours and compact form.<br/></li><li><strong>Winter</strong>: Always bring indoors or under cover before frost. Some are hardy in coastal areas, such as <a href=\"/products/echeveria-elegans\" title=\"Echeveria elegans\">elegans</a>.<br/></li><li><strong>Display</strong>: Perfect for pots, alpine troughs, or mixed succulent planters.</li></ul><p><br/>With the right care, Echeverias will reward you with long-lasting rosettes, vivid colours, and even new plants to share. They are low-maintenance but love consistency: bright light, dry soil, and frost protection are the secrets to success.</p>",
